'''Albert Arnold Gore, Jr.''' (born [[March 31]], [[1948]]) is an [[United States|American]] [[environmentalism|environmental]] [[activist]], author, [[public intellectual]],<ref name=pubint>{{cite web
|url=http://www.foreignpolicy.com/story/cms.php?story_id=4349&page=1
|title=''Foreign Policy'': The World's Top 20 Public Intellectuals 
|accessdate= 2008-07-14
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=July/August 2008
|work= 
|publisher= ''[[Foreign Policy]]''
}}</ref> [[businessperson]], former [[politician]], and former journalist. He served as the forty-fifth [[Vice President of the United States]] from 1993 to 2001 under [[President of the United States|President]] [[Bill Clinton]].

Gore was involved in American politics for over three decades, serving first in the [[United States House of Representatives|U.&nbsp;S. House of Representatives]] (1977&ndash;85) and later in the [[United States Senate|U.&nbsp;S. Senate]] (1985&ndash;93) (representing [[Tennessee]]) before becoming vice president. Known as an ''[[Atari Democrat]]'',<ref name=biosen/> Gore introduced legislation and policies to develop what he called "The [[Information Superhighway]]" (most notably, the [[High Performance Computing and Communication Act of 1991]] which led to the creation of the [[National Information Infrastructure]]). He received a [[List_of_Webby_Award_winners#2005|Webby Award]] for this work in 2005.<ref name=usatoday>{{cite web
|url=http://www.usatoday.com/tech/news/2005-05-04-gore-webby_x.htm 
|title=Webby Awards not laughing at Gore's contribution to Net Former Vice President of the United States 
|accessdate=2008-06-15
|author= A.P.
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=May 5, 2005
|work= 
|publisher= ''[[USA Today]]''
}}</ref><ref name=nyt>{{cite web
|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2005/06/08/arts/08webb.html
|title=Accepting a Webby? Brevity, Please
|accessdate=2008-06-15
|author=
|last= Carr 
|first=David
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=June 8, 2005
|work= 
|publisher= [[American Broadcasting Company]]
}}</ref> 
In 2000, Gore was the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for president in the [[United States presidential election, 2000|presidential election]]. He won the popular vote but ultimately lost to Republican candidate [[George W. Bush]]. A legal controversy over the [[Florida election recount]] was eventually settled in favor of Bush by the [[Bush v. Gore|Supreme Court]].<ref name=Cornell-BushvGore>{{cite web
|url=http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/00-949.ZPC.html
|title=George W. Bush, et al., Petitioners v. Albert Gore, Jr., et al., 531 U.S. 98 (2000)
|accessdate= 2008-06-16
|author= 
|last=
|first=
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= 
|work= 
|publisher=[[Cornell Law School]]
}}</ref>

In 2007, Gore was awarded the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] (together with the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]]) for "efforts to build up and disseminate greater knowledge about man-made climate change, and to lay the foundations for the measures that are needed to counteract such change."<ref name=nobel>{{cite web
|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/peace/laureates/2007/ 
|title=The Nobel Peace Prize 2007 
|accessdate= 2008-06-16
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= 
|work= 
|publisher=nobelprize.org 
}}</ref> He is also the author of the 2006 text, ''[[An Inconvenient Truth: The Planetary Emergency of Global Warming and What We Can Do About It|An Inconvenient Truth]]'' on the topic of global warming and starred in the [[Academy Award for Documentary Feature|Academy Award-winning]] documentary ''[[An Inconvenient Truth]],'' released in conjunction with the book. He helped to organize the 2007 [[benefit concert]] for global warming, ''[[Live Earth]]''.

Gore is currently the founder and chair of [[Alliance for Climate Protection]], the co-founder and chair of [[Generation Investment Management]], the co-founder and chair of the [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award - winning]] American television channel [[Current TV]], a member of the Board of Directors of [[Apple Inc.]], and a senior advisor to [[Google]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web
|url=http://www.algore.com/about.html 
