===Second presidential run (2000)===
{{main article|Al Gore presidential campaign, 2000}}
{{seealso|Bush v. Gore|Florida election recount}}

There was talk of a potential run for president by Gore as early as January 1998.<ref name=wings>{{cite web
|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/special_report/1998/clinton_scandal/51093.stm 
|title=Al Gore: Waiting in the wings
|accessdate= 2008-07-03
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= Jan. 27, 1998
|work= 
|publisher= [[BBC]] 
}}</ref> Gore formally announced his candidacy for president in a speech on June 16, 1999, in Carthage, Tennessee.<ref name=announce2000>{{cite web
|url=http://www.cnn.com/ALLPOLITICS/stories/1999/06/16/president.2000/gore/ 
|title=Gore launches presidential campaign 
|accessdate= 2008-07-03
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= June 16, 1999
|work= 
|publisher= [[CNN]] 
}}</ref> He was introduced by his eldest daughter, [[Karenna Gore Schiff]], who was pregnant at the time with her first child.<ref name=announce2000/> In making the speech, Gore also distanced himself from [[Bill Clinton]], whom he stated had lied to him.<ref name=announce2000/> Gore was "briefly interrupted" by [[AIDS]] protesters claiming Gore was working with the pharmaceutical industry to prevent access to generic medicines for poor nations and chanting "Gore's greed kills."<ref name=announce2000/> Additional speeches were also interrupted by the protesters. Gore responded, "I love this country. I love the First Amendment [...] Let me say in response to those who may have chosen an inappropriate way to make their point, that actually the crisis of AIDS in Africa is one that should command the attention of people in the United States and around the world." Gore also issued a statement saying that he supported efforts to lower the cost of the AIDS drugs, provided that they "are done in a way consistent with international agreements."<ref name=protestAIDS>{{cite web
|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/politics/campaigns/wh2000/stories/gore061899.htm
|title= AIDS Activists Badger Gore Again
|accessdate= 2008-07-03
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors=Charles R. Babcock and Ceci Connolly 
|date= June 18, 1999
|work= 
|publisher= ''[[Washington Post]]''
}}</ref><ref name=briefing>{{cite web
|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9901E4DB153DF931A35754C0A96F958260 
