}}</ref>

On August 13, 2000, Gore announced that he had selected Senator [[Joe Lieberman]] of Connecticut as his vice presidential running mate. Lieberman became "the first person of the [[Jew]]ish faith to run for the nation's second-highest office" ([[Barry Goldwater]], who ran for president in 1964, was of "Jewish origin").<ref name=liebermanobs>{{cite web
|url=http://www.observer.com/node/43265
|title= Joe Lieberman
|accessdate= 2008-07-15
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors=
|date=  August 13, 2000
|work= 
|publisher= ''[[The New York Observer]]''
}}</ref> Lieberman, who was a more conservative Democrat than Gore, had publicly blasted President Clinton for the [[Monica Lewinsky]] affair. Many pundits saw Gore's choice of Lieberman as another way of trying to distance himself from the scandals of the Clinton White House.<ref name=chooses>{{cite web
|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9805E3DD1F3CF93AA3575BC0A9669C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=print 
|title= THE 2000 CAMPAIGN: THE VICE PRESIDENT; Gore and Lieberman Make Tolerance the Centerpiece 
|accessdate= 2008-07-03
|author= 
|last=Sack 
|first=Kevin 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=August 9, 2000 
|work= 
|publisher= ''[[New York Times]]''
}}</ref> Gore's daughter, Karenna, together with her father's former [[Harvard]] roommate [[Tommy Lee Jones]],<ref name=speak>{{cite web
|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0008/16/se.03.html
|title= Joe Lieberman, Karenna Gore Schiff Speak to the Democratic National Convention
|accessdate= 2008-07-03
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors=
|date= August 16, 2000
|work= 
|publisher= ''[[CNN]]''
}}</ref> officially nominated Gore as the Democratic presidential candidate during the [[2000 Democratic National Convention]] in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]].<ref name=nominate>{{cite web
|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/08/16/convention.wrap.02/index.html
|title= Democrats nominate Gore for presidency
|accessdate= 2008-07-03
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors=
|date= August 17, 2000
|work= 
|publisher= ''[[CNN]]''
}}</ref> Gore accepted his party's nomination and spoke about the major themes of his campaign, stating in particular his plan to extend [[Medicare (United States)|Medicare]] to pay for [[prescription drugs]], to work for a sensible universal health-care system.<ref name=nominate/> Soon after the convention, with running mate Joe Lieberman, Gore hit the campaign trail. He and Bush were deadlocked in the polls.<ref name=kickoff>{{cite web
|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/09/04/campaign.wrap/index.html
|title=Bush, Gore kick off fall campaign season with appeal to working families
|accessdate= 2008-07-01
|author= 
|last=Ferullo
|first= Mike
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=September 4, 2000
|work= 
|publisher= [[CNN]]
}}</ref> Gore and Bush participated in three televised debates. While both sides claimed victory after each, Gore was critiqued as either too stiff, too reticent, or too aggressive in contrast to Bush.<ref name=kickoff>{{cite web
|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/10/16/rothenberg.column/index.html
|title=Stuart Rothenberg: Gore, Bush hope third debate is the charm
|accessdate= 2008-07-01
|author= 
|last=Rothenberg
|first= Stuart
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=October 16, 2000
|work= 
|publisher= [[CNN]]
}}</ref><ref name=eludes>{{cite web
|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/10/18/novak.column/index.html
|title=Robert Novak: Big win eludes Gore in final presidential debate
|accessdate= 2008-07-01
|author= 
|last=Novak
|first= Robert
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=October 18, 2000
|work= 
|publisher= [[CNN]]
}}</ref>

On election night, news networks first called Florida for Gore, later retracted the projection, and then called Florida for Bush, before finally retracting that projection as well.<ref name=pbs2000night>{{cite web
|url=http://www.pbs.org/newshour/media/election2000/election_night.html 
|title= Election Night: Media Watch
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= 
|work= 
|publisher= [[PBS]]
}}</ref> Florida's [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Secretary of State]], [[Katherine Harris]], eventually certified Florida's vote count.<ref name=CNN2000>{{cite web
|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/11/26/presidential.election/index.html
|title= Bush begins transition, urges Gore not to contest
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=November 26, 2000 
|work= 
|publisher= [[CNN]]
}}</ref> This led to the [[Florida election recount]], a move to further examine the [[United States presidential election in Florida, 2000|Florida results]].<ref name=CNN2000recount>{{cite web
|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/11/27/gore.transcript/index.html
|title= Transcript: Gore remarks on Florida vote certification
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=November 27, 2000 
|work= 
|publisher= [[CNN]]
}}</ref> 

The Florida recount was stopped a few weeks later by the [[Supreme Court of the United States]]. In the ruling, ''[[Bush v. Gore]]'', the Florida recount was called unconstitutional and that no constitutionally valid recount could be completed by the December 12 deadline, effectively ending the recounts. This 7-2 vote ruled that the standards the [[Florida Supreme Court]] provided for a recount were unconstitutional due to violations of the Equal Protection Clause of the [[Fourteenth Amendment of the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]], and further ruled 5-4 that no constitutionally valid recount could be completed by the December 12 deadline. This case ordered an end to recounting underway in selected Florida counties, effectively giving [[George W. Bush]] a 534 vote victory in Florida and consequently Florida's 25 [[electoral votes]] and the presidency.<ref name=lawcornell>{{cite web
|url=http://www.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/00-949.ZPC.html 
|title=Supreme Court Collection: Bush v. Gore 
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=December 12, 2000 
|work= 
|publisher= [[Cornell University]] 
}}</ref> The results of the decision led to Gore winning the [[popular vote]] by approximately 500,000 votes nationwide, but receiving 266 electoral votes to Bush's 271 (1 [[District of Columbia]] Elector abstained).<ref name=2000time>{{cite web
|url=http://www.time.com/time/pacific/magazine/20001120/schlesinger.html  
|title="It's a Mess, But We've Been Through It Before" 
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=September 6, 2006
|work= 
|publisher=''[[TIME]]'' 
}}</ref> On December 13, 2000, Gore conceded the election.<ref name=cnnconcede>{{cite web
|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ALLPOLITICS/stories/12/13/gore.ends.campaign/index.html 
|title=Gore concedes presidential election 
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=December 13, 2000
|work= 
|publisher= [[CNN]]
}}</ref> Gore strongly disagreed with the Court's decision, but in his concession speech stated that, "for the sake of our unity as a people and the strength of our democracy, I offer my concession."<ref name=cnnconcedespeech>{{cite web
|url=http://edition.cnn.com/ELECTION/2000/transcripts/121300/t651213.html
|title= VICE PRESIDENT AL GORE DELIVERS REMARKS
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last=Gore
|first=Al 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=December 13, 2000
|work= 
|publisher= [[CNN]]
}}</ref>

The 2000 election is the subject of a 2008 [[television movie|made-for-TV movie]] directed by [[Jay Roach]], produced by, and starring [[Kevin Spacey]] called ''[[Recount (film)|Recount]].'' It premiered on the [[HBO]] cable network on May 25, 2008.<ref name=nytreview>{{cite web
|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/05/23/arts/television/23reco.html?_r=1&ref=television&oref=slogin
