}}</ref>

==2004 and 2008 presidential elections==
===Potential presidential runs===
[[Image:Al Gore - Ohhh, you aren't going to get me on this one.jpg|thumb|[[Chris Anderson (TED)|Chris Anderson]] asks: "Will you run again?" Gore replies that he is not going to get caught on that one.]]

Gore was a potential candidate for the [[United States presidential election, 2004|2004 Presidential Election]] (a bumper sticker, "Re-elect Gore in 2004!" was popular).<ref name=bumpertsticker>{{cite web
|url=http://www.demstore.com/cgi-local/SoftCart.exe/scstore/Gore/99-3001-00.shtml?E+scstore 
|title=Gore in 2004 Bumper Sticker 
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= 
|work= 
|publisher=demstore.com 
}}</ref> On December 16, 2002, however, Gore announced that he would not run in 2004.<ref name=>{{cite web
|url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/ALLPOLITICS/12/15/gore/ 
|title=Gore Says He Won't Run in 2004
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=December 16, 2002 
|work= 
|publisher= [[CNN]]
}}</ref> Despite Gore taking himself out of the race, a handful of his supporters formed a national campaign to "[[political draft|draft]]" him into running. The draft movement, however, failed to convince Gore to run.<ref name=>{{cite web
|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4176/is_20030331/ai_n14545655  
|title=Oaklander leads effort to draft Gore in '04 
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
