|last=Richman 
|first=Josh 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=March 31, 2003 
|work= 
|publisher= [[Oakland Tribune]]
}}</ref> In 2003 (and later in 2007), Gore's son Albert was arrested for possession of illegal drugs.<ref>{{cite news|title=Al Gore's son charged with pot possession|url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/US/South/12/20/gore.son/|publisher=CNN|date=2003-12-21|accessdate=2008-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Al Gore<U+2019>s son arrested on drug charges|url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/19601277/|work=MSNBC.com|publisher=AP|date=2007-07-04|accessdate=2008-07-30}}</ref> 

The prospect of a Gore candidacy once again arose between 2006 to early 2008 in regard to the [[United States presidential election, 2008|2008 presidential election]]. Although Gore frequently stated that he had "no plans to run,"
he did not reject the possibility of future involvement in politics which led to speculation that he might.<ref name = "nytimes-door">{{cite web
|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2007/12/10/gore-leaves-door-open/ 
|title=  Gore Leaves the Door Open
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last=Alexovich 
|first=Ariel 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=December 10, 2007 
|work= 
|publisher= ''[[New York Times]]''
}}</ref><ref name=newsweekrunning>{{cite web
|url=http://www.newsweek.com/id/77828 
|title=Why Isn't Gore Running? 
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last=Hirsh 
|first=Michael
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= December 13, 2007
|work= 
|publisher= ''[[Newsweek]] Magazine''
}}</ref><ref name=timetemp>{{cite web
