===Endorsements and VP speculation===
Although he had decided not to run in the [[United States presidential election, 2004|2004 U.S. presidential election]], Gore became involved in the process in December 2003, when he endorsed [[Governor of Vermont|Vermont governor]] [[Howard Dean]] weeks before the first primary of the election cycle.<ref name=>{{cite web
|url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/ALLPOLITICS/12/09/elec04.prez.gore.dean 
|title= Al Gore endorses Howard Dean
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= December 10, 2003 
|work= 
|publisher= [[CNN]]
}}</ref> Gore preferred Dean over Lieberman because Lieberman supported the war and Gore did not.<ref name=look>{{cite web
|url=http://www.observer.com/2008/look-whos-back-its-gore-and-lieberman-08 
|title=Look Who's Back: It's Gore and Lieberman in '08 
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last=Kornacki   
|first= Steve
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= June 20, 2008
|work= 
|publisher= The New York Observer
}}</ref> Gore was severely criticized for this endorsement by eight Democratic contenders particularly since he did not endorse his former running mate [[Joe Lieberman]].<ref name=aim/><ref name=>{{cite web
|url=http://www.cnn.com/2003/ALLPOLITICS/12/09/elec04.prez.debate.ap/index.html
|title=Gore's endorsement stirs debate
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=December 10, 2003
|work= 
|publisher= [[CNN]]
}}</ref> Dean's campaign soon became a target of attacks and eventually failed, with Gore's early endorsement being credited as a factor. In ''[[The New York Times]],'' Dean stated: "I actually do think the endorsement of Al Gore began the decline." The ''Times'' further noted that "Dean instantly amplified his statement to indicate that the endorsement from Mr. Gore, a powerhouse of the establishment, so threatened the other Democratic candidates that they began the attacks on his candidacy that helped derail it."<ref name=>{{cite web
|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B03E5D81F3BF93BA35751C0A9629C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=print 
|title=An Endorsement From Gore Became a Dubious Prize 
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last=Bumiller
|first=Elisabeth
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date=2004-02-08
|work= New York Times
}}</ref> Dean's former campaign manager, Joe Trippi, also stated that after Gore's endorsement of Dean, "alarm bells went off in every newsroom in the country, in every other campaign in the country," indicating that if something did not change, Dean would be the nominee.<ref name=>{{cite web
|url= http://www.wired.com/politics/law/news/2004/02/62225
|title= Trippi: Net Politics Here to Stay
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last=Shachtman    
|first= Noah
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= February 10, 2004
|work= 
|publisher= [[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]
}}</ref> Later, in March 2004, Gore endorsed [[John Kerry]] and gave Kerry $6 million in funds left over from his own unsuccessful 2000 bid.<ref name=>{{cite web
|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2004/04/29/politics/campaign/29GORE.html?ex=1398571200&en=42fe540e881650bf&ei=5007&partner=USERLAND  
|title= Gore Giving Leftover Cash of $6 Million to Back Kerry
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= 
|first= 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= GLEN JUSTICE and KATHARINE Q. SEELYE
|date= April 29, 2004
|work= 
|publisher= ''[[New York Times]]''
}}</ref> Gore also opened the [[2004 Democratic National Convention]].<ref name=>{{cite web
|url=http://www.pbs.org/newshour/vote2004/demconvention/speeches/gore.html 
|title=VICE PRESIDENT AL GORE at the 2004 Democratic National Convention
|accessdate= 2008-07-18
|author= 
|last= Gore
|first=Al 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= 
|work= 
|publisher= [[PBS]]
}}</ref>

A few years later, Gore initially refused to endorse any of the candidates for the [[United States presidential election, 2008|2008 presidential election]].<ref name=undecided>{{cite web
|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/politicsNews/idUSL2077281320080520 
|title=Gore says undecided on U.S. candidate endorsement
|accessdate= 2008-06-16
|author= 
|last=
|first=
|authorlink= 
|coauthors=Jeffrey Heller & Avida Landu 
|date= 
|work= 
|publisher= Reuters
}}</ref> ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' and ''[[Newsweek]]'' magazines interpreted this reticence as a sign that he would come out of a brokered 2008 [[Democratic National Convention]] as a "compromise candidate" if the party decided it could not nominate a candidate.<ref name=answer>{{cite web
|url=http://www.time.com/time/nation/article/0,8599,1725678,00.html 
|title=Is Al Gore the Answer? 
|accessdate= 2008-06-16
|author= 
|last=Klein 
|first=Joe 
|authorlink= 
|coauthors= 
|date= 
|work= 
|publisher= ''[[Time]]''
}}</ref><ref name=rescue>{{cite web
